From bf3aa5d425b429739e487c7cd741b5fcf64688d2 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Bill Hlavacek <bill.hlavacek@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 23 May 2026 01:52:11 -0600
Subject: [PATCH 06/14] bngsim: fix product-molecularity check for multi-bond
 ring-opening

TransformationSet::checkMolecularity enforces product-side molecularity for
unimolecular unbinding rules (the Issue #48 carry): a dissociation
"A.B -> A + B" must only fire when breaking the bond actually separates the
match into different connected components. The check tested each deleted bond
in isolation via canReachExcludingBond, excluding a single bond and asking
whether the partners stayed connected.

That wrongly blocks rules that delete several bonds at once to open a cyclic
complex. A symmetric two-bond homodimer dissociation
(M(h!1,f!2).M(h!2,f!1) -> M(h,f) + M(h,f)) removes both ring bonds together;
each bond alone leaves the partners connected through the other, so the
per-bond test returns false and the reverse reaction never fires. The dimer
becomes a kinetic trap and the system over-assembles relative to the network
ODE and to upstream NFsim (internal#57).

Gather every bond the rule's UNBINDING transforms will delete and exclude the
whole set at once (canReachExcludingBonds). A pair is judged separated only if
it is unreachable after all the rule's bonds are removed. Single-bond ring
dissociations that genuinely fail molecularity (internal#54/#55) stay
blocked, since their lone bond's removal still leaves the partners connected
through the rest of the cycle.
